``It ends the speculation,'' said Leonard Garment, who served as acting White House counsel during the investigation into the Watergate break-in, and published a book called ``In Search of Deep Throat'' in 2000. Ferreting out Deep Throat's identity has long been a favorite topic in Washington and beyond, and the search has engaged former Nixon administration officials who dealt with the consequences of his leaks, intrepid journalism students eager to solve one of a prior generation's abiding enigmas, and many an armchair sleuth. Another strain of thought focused on officials in the FBI. 